my name is Teresa Davoli. I'm associate professor at NYU

5
00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:18.100
Medical School, and I'm very happy to chair this session

6
00:00:19.100 --> 00:00:23.080
on the latest findings in the aneuploidy field.

7
00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:27.000
We will span the full arc of tumorigenesis from cancer

8
00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:28.140
initiation to

9
00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:31.940
how we could use aneuploidy as a way to predict

10
00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:37.200
the tumor microenvironment and the patient's

11
00:00:37.220 --> 00:00:41.080
response. We have great speakers, Sam Aparicio from

12
00:00:41.120 --> 00:00:45.060
University of British Columbia in Vancouver, and Nick Navin and Andy

13
00:00:45.080 --> 00:00:48.140
Anderson, you already heard from him as well, and

14
00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:49.240
myself.

15
00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:52.560
And so, before we start,

16
00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:55.080
I just wanted to

17
00:00:56.840 --> 00:01:00.320
advertise. I just wanted to mention a special AACR

18
00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:04.020
conference that will be organized next year, early next year,

19
00:01:04.181 --> 00:01:06.600
2027, in Vancouver.

20
00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:11.640
And this special conference is really on the topic of

21
00:01:11.780 --> 00:01:14.120
aneuploidy and chromosomally complex cancers.

22
00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:16.960
So all of you should be quite interested in

23
00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:21.960
joining this conference and please advertise it

24
00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:26.220
with your colleagues as well. And it's organized by Sam Aparicio as

25
00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:28.720
well as Sharon Kantor and Carlyn Chimprich.

26
00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:32.280
So they're putting together an exciting set of speakers

27
00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:33.560
for all of us.

28
00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:35.200
And so

29
00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:39.280
we just have a few more minutes,

30
00:01:40.580 --> 00:01:41.640
but I think we can

31
00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:46.580
start with the first talk that will be given by

32
00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:48.800
Sam Aparicio.

33
00:01:50.140 --> 00:01:53.740
Sam, as I said, is from University of British Columbia in Vancouver.

34
00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:58.020
Thank you so much for joining us, Sam, and we look forward to your

35
00:01:58.060 --> 00:01:58.380
talk.

36
00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:04.860
Great. Thank you. And I'd like to begin by thanking AACR and

37
00:02:04.900 --> 00:02:08.539
the organizers for the opportunity to talk about some of our

38
00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:08.900
work,

39
00:02:10.301 --> 00:02:13.540
in the origins of mutations, and I slightly liberally interpreted

40
00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:17.580
the theme of the session as well to include a little bit on aging of breast

41
00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:17.980
tissue.

42
00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:20.640
So I'd like to present

43
00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:25.320
two short stories. One about the origins

44
00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:28.930
of founder gene dosage mutations in the breast, and

45
00:02:30.260 --> 00:02:33.660
I think we're going to hear a lot more about that from Nick, from his seminal work.

46
00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:37.870
And then some more recent work on the relationship between

47
00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:41.760
chronological age and changes in cell composition in the breast.

48
00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:46.740
Now, to introduce the topic, for those of you who don't

49
00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:50.180
necessarily work on breast cancer or

50
00:02:50.900 --> 00:02:54.060
mutational processes, I just want to remind us

51
00:02:54.120 --> 00:02:58.080
that all forms of mutation of course can contribute

52
00:02:58.120 --> 00:03:02.100
to cancer. But we've been studying for many years

53
00:03:02.140 --> 00:03:05.220
a particular form of mutation, which involves

54
00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:08.280
the types of topological

55
00:03:09.260 --> 00:03:13.220
shuffling and gene dosage changes that can occur

56
00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:16.720
in cancer tissues. Because

57
00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:18.720
it turns out that

58
00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:23.920
mutations that copy paste genes or delete genes or invert them are

59
00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:24.620
quite common,

60
00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:29.120
and span a spectrum from rather small

61
00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:33.620
scale events all the way up to whole genome duplication where the entire

62
00:03:33.660 --> 00:03:36.200
gene complement gets duplicated.

63
00:03:36.820 --> 00:03:40.660
And these have a particular significance in cancer development because

64
00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:44.900
unlike single nucleotide variants, which are very, very

65
00:03:44.940 --> 00:03:45.360
prevalent,

66
00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:49.900
a single mutational event can, in principle, disrupt genome

67
00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:53.700
organization and can affect potentially the expression of hundreds of

68
00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:55.520
genes,

69
00:03:56.720 --> 00:03:59.320
through altered gene dosage and topological domains.

70
00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:02.760
So they have a particular mechanistic significance.

71
00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:07.300
And the impact of copy structural variant

72
00:04:08.140 --> 00:04:11.780
mutation on transcription has now been very well

73
00:04:11.790 --> 00:04:14.730
documented across many cancers. This is work taken

74
00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:17.620
from the Pan-Cancer Working Group

75
00:04:18.481 --> 00:04:20.560
papers that appeared a few years ago.

76
00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:24.100
There have been many similar studies that have shown this, that the

77
00:04:25.080 --> 00:04:29.060
mutational copy number burden is very variable between

78
00:04:29.100 --> 00:04:32.960
cancers. Cancers such as breast and ovarian cancer tend to be

79
00:04:33.020 --> 00:04:36.460
highly mutated in this way, whereas, for example, some

80
00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:40.220
sarcomas, much less so. But when you look at the

81
00:04:40.230 --> 00:04:44.060
effect size, transcription is the thing

82
00:04:44.100 --> 00:04:45.760
which is most strongly affected,

83
00:04:46.900 --> 00:04:50.680
over all mutation classes. And copy number changes are the biggest

84
00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:54.400
single contributor to that. So they have some

85
00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:56.620
mechanistic importance. Now,

86
00:04:58.260 --> 00:05:02.100
it's now well over a decade ago, 15 years or so ago, we had started

87
00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:06.400
trying to look at the genomes of established cancers,

88
00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:10.760
established breast cancers. And we, together with TCGA and ICGC,

89
00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:14.680
there were a number of international efforts to characterize

90
00:05:14.960 --> 00:05:18.940
the genomes of cancers. And we arrived at the observation

91
00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:22.880
that when you look over all breast cancers, if you were to examine

92
00:05:22.940 --> 00:05:26.540
the genome and look at the copy number amplification and deletion map, this

93
00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:31.060
plot in the center here shows the prevalence of chromosomal

94
00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:34.820
alterations that either result in a gain of a chromosome or a loss of a

95
00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:35.360
chromosome,

96
00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:39.900
or chromosomal segments, that you can see that there's a particular chromosomally

97
00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:42.100
restricted pattern in terms of prevalence.

98
00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:45.620
And we now understand that these amplifications and deletions

99
00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:47.520
are key for

100
00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:52.220
mediating oncogene drivers and altering the function of tumor

101
00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:55.160
suppressors. And, in fact, they

102
00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:59.240
also co-segregate patient behavior.

103
00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:03.080
So we know that these cancers with different alterations have different

104
00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:04.500
biological behaviors shown

105
00:06:05.580 --> 00:06:07.820
here in these survival curves.Now,

106
00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:12.060
all of this analysis was conducted with bulk tissues.

107
00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:15.880
We took tumors and literally put them in a blender and applied the

108
00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:19.440
genomics of the day, which has been bulk genomics,

109
00:06:20.620 --> 00:06:24.300
looking at the tissues. But this doesn't teach us so much

110
00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:27.940
about where and when this gene dosage landscape might

111
00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:28.480
emerge.

112
00:06:29.780 --> 00:06:31.530
And so to look at that question,

113
00:06:32.960 --> 00:06:35.890
a few years ago, we decided to

114
00:06:36.280 --> 00:06:40.140
start studying the normal epithelium of the

115
00:06:40.220 --> 00:06:42.380
breast to ask the question:

116
00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:47.560
Do we observe gene dosage mutations, and if so, where do they

117
00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:48.040
occur?

118
00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:51.100
And to do this, we

119
00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:55.400
chose to take an approach of single-cell genome sequencing.

120
00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:58.340
This is something that we implemented a few years ago.

121
00:06:58.470 --> 00:07:02.080
We were inspired by Nick's early work in developing single-cell

122
00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:05.560
techniques for looking at genomes and transcriptomes.

123
00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:09.940
And this method simply takes dissociated cells from whatever

124
00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.150
tissue and allows you to do shallow

125
00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:17.060
transposition, non-amplification-based reads

126
00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:19.930
over the genome of lots of single genomes,

127
00:07:20.840 --> 00:07:22.530
and then read them out and look at

128
00:07:23.520 --> 00:07:27.300
copy number and structure. Now, to do this in the

129
00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:31.080
breast, what we did was we took normal breast

130
00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:34.640
tissue and flow sorted the epithelium

131
00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:37.920
into the two major lineages that have been described.

132
00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:40.540
So for those of you not familiar with the human breast,

133
00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:45.860
broadly, there are two epithelial lineages referred to as luminal,

134
00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:49.720
in which there are some subsets of cells that have been described.

135
00:07:49.730 --> 00:07:51.370
These are the milk-producing cells.

136
00:07:51.880 --> 00:07:55.800
And then there's a basal myoepithelium surrounded by a basement membrane.

137
00:07:55.840 --> 00:07:57.920
The myoepithelium is the contractile layer.

138
00:07:58.590 --> 00:07:58.840
And

139
00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:01.660
we were particularly interested in this

140
00:08:02.640 --> 00:08:05.000
set in patients who are

141
00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:10.240
genetically wild-type, but also through a collaboration with Joan

142
00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:15.160
Brugge and the Gray Project in Boston, in looking

143
00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:18.380
at carriers of BRCA1 and BRCA2

144
00:08:19.060 --> 00:08:22.720
germline alleles, which are susceptibility genes for breast

145
00:08:22.780 --> 00:08:25.170
cancer. So we took these samples, flow sorted them,

146
00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:28.320
and then looked at the constitution.

147
00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:32.900
Now, the way that we're representing the mutational

148
00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:36.821
impact, the first observation in these heat maps,

149
00:08:37.720 --> 00:08:41.040
every line in this heat map represents a single genome,

150
00:08:41.800 --> 00:08:45.260
and the gray colors imply that the cells are diploid, the normal

151
00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:49.120
chromosomal state, whereas a yellow or orange color is a gain, and blue is a

152
00:08:49.160 --> 00:08:52.780
loss. And you can see that there are a number of cells, these are four different

153
00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:53.340
patients

154
00:08:54.780 --> 00:08:57.960
among the BRCA and wild type, that contain

155
00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:02.020
chromosomal gains and losses, which look to be chromosomally

156
00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:05.760
restricted. And the first observation is, first of all, we could see

157
00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:07.020
these, and particularly

158
00:09:07.920 --> 00:09:11.840
gains in chromosome 1q, which is

159
00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:16.340
part of the cancer landscape, as well as losses

160
00:09:16.360 --> 00:09:18.690
in chromosome 10 and some other chromosomes.

161
00:09:19.170 --> 00:09:22.329
And so we could see that there was a pattern, and it was restricted, but

162
00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:26.260
also rather infrequent. So very few cells have these

163
00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:30.300
aberrations. The vast majority of cells here, much less

164
00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:32.240
than 1% of the cells seem to have

165
00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:34.860
copy number gains.

166
00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:40.340
The fact that we could see many cells with apparently the same gain

167
00:09:41.140 --> 00:09:44.940
immediately posed another question, which is whether these are really clonal

168
00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.540
amplifications or whether they might be occurring independently.

169
00:09:48.580 --> 00:09:51.540
And it's quite hard to date these

170
00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:55.740
phylogenetically with this process, but one thing you can do

171
00:09:56.360 --> 00:09:58.380
is look at the alleles that are present

172
00:09:59.360 --> 00:10:03.040
and phase them. And phasing the alleles would tend to

173
00:10:03.100 --> 00:10:06.960
suggest that because we see roughly equal representation of both

174
00:10:07.060 --> 00:10:10.960
A and B alleles in these cells, that it's probably

175
00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:14.000
more compatible with these being sporadically recurrent events.

176
00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:17.820
Although, it doesn't preclude that eventually you will get a clonal

177
00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:19.360
amplification that leads to

178
00:10:21.660 --> 00:10:25.459
canalization of one of these. But at least the initial observation

179
00:10:25.519 --> 00:10:28.600
was that allelic phasing suggested these might be sporadic.

180
00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:30.460
And

181
00:10:31.340 --> 00:10:31.670
the other

182
00:10:32.860 --> 00:10:36.540
observation is that we found mutations in the luminal

183
00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:38.200
cells quite prevalent.

184
00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:42.480
We did not find them so much in the basal cells, so it appears to

185
00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:46.420
be lineage restricted. In other words, the copy

186
00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:50.380
number aberrations seem to be just in the one cell type.

187
00:10:51.300 --> 00:10:55.040
And that's important because there's been some debate, particularly amongst

188
00:10:55.080 --> 00:10:58.260
different subtypes of breast cancers, to the exact origin

189
00:10:59.660 --> 00:11:01.120
of the landscape.

190
00:11:01.980 --> 00:11:04.780
There are breast cancers that have more of a basal

191
00:11:05.120 --> 00:11:06.600
myoepithelial phenotype,

192
00:11:07.480 --> 00:11:11.460
but in pure, normal basal epithelium, we didn't see so many

193
00:11:11.500 --> 00:11:15.460
of these mutations. The other striking feature is

194
00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:15.660
that

195
00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:20.360
the pattern is partially reflective of the breast cancer landscape.

196
00:11:21.120 --> 00:11:24.440
This plot reproduces, again, the TCGA

197
00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:27.640
ICGC Metabricks copy number landscape.

198
00:11:27.670 --> 00:11:31.660
And what you can see is that 1q is a very prevalent event in

199
00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:35.280
established breast cancers, as is loss of 10, but clearly

200
00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:37.500
established cancers have many more events.

201
00:11:38.620 --> 00:11:42.560
Interestingly, we see losses in chromosome 7,

202
00:11:42.660 --> 00:11:43.260
but we

203
00:11:44.220 --> 00:11:47.720
did not see were gains in chromosome 8q, suggesting that

204
00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:52.420
this is a very prominent amplification event in breast cancer,

205
00:11:52.480 --> 00:11:53.520
but we didn't observe it,

206
00:11:54.520 --> 00:11:57.040
suggesting it really is happening potentially

207
00:11:57.080 --> 00:12:00.896
laterAnd the other observation here is

208
00:12:00.936 --> 00:12:04.736
that we found this in tissues. We also looked in cultured

209
00:12:04.816 --> 00:12:08.636
mammary epithelial cells, such as we had available at the time, and we've

210
00:12:08.646 --> 00:12:12.446
since extended this to other studies where we've looked at organoids that

211
00:12:12.476 --> 00:12:14.896
we've cultured from mammary epithelium.

212
00:12:14.956 --> 00:12:16.516
We have quite a large bank of

213
00:12:17.356 --> 00:12:19.616
cryopreserved normal mammary epithelium.

214
00:12:20.356 --> 00:12:23.856
We do see some cells that contain the gains in 1q

215
00:12:23.896 --> 00:12:27.176
and loss of 10, but much, much less prevalent.

216
00:12:28.136 --> 00:12:31.636
This is frustrating because we'd like to study this

217
00:12:31.676 --> 00:12:33.816
phenomenon functionally, but capturing this

218
00:12:34.676 --> 00:12:37.576
in organoids, for us at least, seems to be quite hard.

219
00:12:38.576 --> 00:12:42.236
And it raises the question of what's the real difference between cultured

220
00:12:42.316 --> 00:12:44.806
organoids and breast tissues that might account for this,

221
00:12:45.776 --> 00:12:47.496
and this we don't know.

222
00:12:48.616 --> 00:12:51.196
The lineage bias extends to co-occurrence.

223
00:12:51.276 --> 00:12:52.016
So we know that

224
00:12:52.816 --> 00:12:53.756
with 1q

225
00:12:55.176 --> 00:12:56.776
gain and loss of 10,

226
00:12:57.636 --> 00:13:01.496
in some cases, these apparent losses are

227
00:13:01.556 --> 00:13:05.296
actually due to fusion translocations which lead to a gain loss event, and that's

228
00:13:05.336 --> 00:13:08.776
been described in a number of publications and we observed

229
00:13:08.786 --> 00:13:12.536
this. And we also saw a degree of genotype

230
00:13:12.636 --> 00:13:13.016
bias,

231
00:13:14.196 --> 00:13:14.756
in that

232
00:13:16.016 --> 00:13:19.756
there was more bias to these co-events in the

233
00:13:19.796 --> 00:13:23.636
BRCA1 and BRCA2 heterozygous patients than there

234
00:13:23.656 --> 00:13:27.116
was over wild type, although the differences were quite modest in

235
00:13:27.156 --> 00:13:28.996
absolute terms.

236
00:13:30.856 --> 00:13:31.836
Finally, the

237
00:13:33.296 --> 00:13:35.096
question of aneuploidy itself.

238
00:13:36.516 --> 00:13:37.076
We saw

239
00:13:38.056 --> 00:13:40.836
very high aneuploidy that was cancer-like occurring

240
00:13:40.846 --> 00:13:44.816
predominantly in the BRCA1/2 heterozygotes

241
00:13:44.836 --> 00:13:46.976
and much less in the wild type epithelium.

242
00:13:47.656 --> 00:13:51.456
And when you look at the ploidy and rank it in terms of its correlation

243
00:13:52.056 --> 00:13:55.926
pattern with established breast cancers versus ploidy, you see a lot

244
00:13:55.956 --> 00:13:59.136
of cells that can have high ploidy but actually have very little

245
00:14:00.096 --> 00:14:02.686
correspondence to a cancer-like phenotype.

246
00:14:03.246 --> 00:14:06.976
And it's these cells over here that were more in the BRCA1 and

247
00:14:06.996 --> 00:14:10.896
BRCA2 carriers. And we think that this may represent

248
00:14:10.936 --> 00:14:14.856
lesions that were microscopically invisible as precursor lesions but

249
00:14:14.876 --> 00:14:18.376
were already, say, partially on their way to forming more

250
00:14:18.436 --> 00:14:21.336
established cancers, although we need a better

251
00:14:22.036 --> 00:14:25.836
histomorphological correlation to really address that.

252
00:14:26.716 --> 00:14:26.876
So,

253
00:14:28.056 --> 00:14:28.506
this was,

254
00:14:29.376 --> 00:14:33.036
I think, one of the things I want to mention here that we were fortunate enough to

255
00:14:33.076 --> 00:14:36.946
be able to publish this at the same time that Nick produced his study, and I

256
00:14:36.956 --> 00:14:39.045
think we're going to hear about that in detail,

257
00:14:40.116 --> 00:14:41.676
where there were similar findings.

258
00:14:43.136 --> 00:14:46.936
We think that there is particular significance to the

259
00:14:46.956 --> 00:14:50.256
chromosomal gains and losses. I also want to highlight for those of you who are

260
00:14:50.296 --> 00:14:52.496
thinking about this field, that there have been a number of papers.

261
00:14:53.156 --> 00:14:57.096
I'm highlighting a couple here from the Elledge Lab and the Shelza

262
00:14:57.156 --> 00:14:58.976
lab that have actually looked functionally

263
00:14:59.996 --> 00:15:02.796
at the roles of chromosome 1q using model systems.

264
00:15:02.876 --> 00:15:06.286
And it seems clear that 1q gains in particular,

265
00:15:07.396 --> 00:15:11.186
can confer selective advantage, some of which may be mediated

266
00:15:11.216 --> 00:15:15.076
by Notch signaling. There are other things on 1q such as MDM genes which

267
00:15:15.116 --> 00:15:18.996
may be related to p53 function. And I think that this

268
00:15:19.006 --> 00:15:22.936
is actually a very fruitful area for further investigation because there's a clear

269
00:15:22.996 --> 00:15:26.796
pointer to this being some kind of an important founder event, but the

270
00:15:26.916 --> 00:15:30.876
actual fitness that's conveyed by it, I think is something

271
00:15:30.916 --> 00:15:32.476
that needs looking into further.

272
00:15:33.576 --> 00:15:37.456
Okay, for the second part, I'd just like to then address a

273
00:15:37.956 --> 00:15:41.896
related question, which is that we see that there

274
00:15:41.936 --> 00:15:45.396
are these lineage copy number mutations that occur in

275
00:15:45.456 --> 00:15:49.296
normal tissues. We think they're probably age-related,

276
00:15:50.356 --> 00:15:52.956
and that's been shown in other work.

277
00:15:53.616 --> 00:15:57.196
And it raises the question of how does the actual composition and

278
00:15:57.276 --> 00:15:59.056
function of the breast change with age?

279
00:15:59.896 --> 00:16:03.136
And this is epidemiologically important.

280
00:16:04.276 --> 00:16:08.036
Early work by Malcolm Pike, who looked into the epidemiology of breast

281
00:16:08.096 --> 00:16:11.416
cancer incidence, clearly established that there's an

282
00:16:11.496 --> 00:16:15.276
age-correlated incidence of breast cancer and also

283
00:16:15.316 --> 00:16:18.796
raised the idea that, in terms of breast tissue

284
00:16:18.955 --> 00:16:19.376
aging,

285
00:16:20.496 --> 00:16:24.316
there's a sort of rate of aging change which happens over

286
00:16:24.636 --> 00:16:27.876
the lifetime of an individual that's strongly

287
00:16:28.496 --> 00:16:30.396
correlated with the onset of

288
00:16:31.556 --> 00:16:32.136
menopause.

289
00:16:33.196 --> 00:16:36.236
So the changes in post endocrine signaling that happen.

290
00:16:37.296 --> 00:16:41.166
And more recent work looking at SNVs has established that there's

291
00:16:41.216 --> 00:16:44.876
a strong age-correlated incidence

292
00:16:44.976 --> 00:16:47.236
of SNVs, which we would expect,

293
00:16:48.116 --> 00:16:51.836
to see if this age correlation is

294
00:16:51.876 --> 00:16:52.116
real.

295
00:16:52.996 --> 00:16:56.676
So to look at the age-related changes, we took advantage of

296
00:16:57.476 --> 00:17:01.056
another collection of cancer-free individual breast

297
00:17:01.116 --> 00:17:02.776
cancers which we had previously

298
00:17:03.576 --> 00:17:06.237
constructed into a microarray. This comprised

299
00:17:07.176 --> 00:17:10.777
537 patients with a range of ages.

300
00:17:12.517 --> 00:17:14.416
We took advantage of some of the latest

301
00:17:15.237 --> 00:17:18.896
single-cell spatial imaging methods, imaging mass cytometry, and

302
00:17:18.956 --> 00:17:20.536
Xenium to look at transcripts.

303
00:17:21.576 --> 00:17:24.796
And again, inspired by Nick's work on the Atlas,

304
00:17:25.596 --> 00:17:29.566
defining cell types in the breast cancer, we wanted to ask how many of

305
00:17:29.596 --> 00:17:33.096
these cell types can we find and how do they change?

306
00:17:33.256 --> 00:17:36.536
How do their relationships change as a function of age?

307
00:17:37.596 --> 00:17:41.476
And so to do this, we took the reduction mammoplasties and the cores.

308
00:17:42.156 --> 00:17:42.416
We

309
00:17:43.536 --> 00:17:47.316
identified something like over 3 million cells in the 1,700 tissue

310
00:17:47.396 --> 00:17:47.706
cores,

311
00:17:48.596 --> 00:17:50.796
imaged with IMC. We also classified

312
00:17:51.616 --> 00:17:55.186
histomorphological changes of normal epithelium

313
00:17:56.456 --> 00:18:00.386
in order to be able to classify cells in the stroma as well as

314
00:18:00.416 --> 00:18:02.136
the epithelium,

315
00:18:03.016 --> 00:18:06.956
and then used dimensional reduction and clustering to identify

316
00:18:06.996 --> 00:18:09.156
cell types based both on the IMC,

317
00:18:10.056 --> 00:18:13.896
and on the Xenium subset.The

318
00:18:13.936 --> 00:18:17.276
main difference, there's a strong overlap between these two methods.

319
00:18:17.896 --> 00:18:21.756
The main difference is that the transcriptional data sets give us a much richer

320
00:18:21.856 --> 00:18:24.926
look at metabolic and other functional states of

321
00:18:24.976 --> 00:18:28.816
cells compared, say, with the antibody set, which gives

322
00:18:28.856 --> 00:18:31.216
us great resolution in terms of protein markers.

323
00:18:32.596 --> 00:18:36.176
And so then we can ask, how does the spatial context of the

324
00:18:36.216 --> 00:18:38.755
epithelium change as a function of age?

325
00:18:39.676 --> 00:18:43.616
Now, to get at this, the other important element is to do some image

326
00:18:43.676 --> 00:18:47.516
processing, both in terms of segmenting cells, but also

327
00:18:47.576 --> 00:18:51.036
to identify macro structures. So we were interested

328
00:18:51.096 --> 00:18:55.016
in the terminal ductal lobular unit structure of the

329
00:18:55.096 --> 00:18:56.496
breast, which is a branching

330
00:18:57.336 --> 00:19:01.056
morphological structure. We wanted to learn about the differences between

331
00:19:01.136 --> 00:19:03.596
ductal regions and lobular regions.

332
00:19:03.916 --> 00:19:07.656
And so we created tissue masks to segment this as well as segmenting the

333
00:19:07.716 --> 00:19:09.896
cells and pull out these features.

334
00:19:11.316 --> 00:19:15.256
So the overall findings here are that there's a general cellular

335
00:19:15.316 --> 00:19:19.176
decline with age, perhaps not surprising, but most tissue

336
00:19:19.236 --> 00:19:22.296
elements go down. There are just fewer cells,

337
00:19:23.756 --> 00:19:23.996
and

338
00:19:25.236 --> 00:19:25.856
particularly

339
00:19:26.936 --> 00:19:30.756
epithelial cells. But then we can ask, are there

340
00:19:30.856 --> 00:19:33.096
specific changes in relationships?

341
00:19:33.706 --> 00:19:37.356
And when we look at the number of heterotypic interactions, so

342
00:19:37.376 --> 00:19:41.206
between distinctive cell types and inflammatory

343
00:19:41.336 --> 00:19:44.786
cells, what we see is that, yes, there are more

344
00:19:46.576 --> 00:19:47.736
endothelial cells,

345
00:19:50.556 --> 00:19:54.356
there are more inflammatory macrophages, more fibroblasts.

346
00:19:54.956 --> 00:19:58.556
CD20 B cells seem to be reduced.

347
00:19:59.856 --> 00:20:01.236
And we see that

348
00:20:03.156 --> 00:20:06.776
these changes also occur with dendritic cells, not replaced here, but there seem to

349
00:20:06.816 --> 00:20:09.356
be fewer dendritic cells as patients age.

350
00:20:10.116 --> 00:20:11.776
And these changes

351
00:20:12.916 --> 00:20:13.536
lead to

352
00:20:14.536 --> 00:20:17.976
decreased cellularity within lobules, which is where the

353
00:20:18.036 --> 00:20:21.636
majority of epithelial cells are

354
00:20:21.696 --> 00:20:25.576
clustered, and somewhat increased in ductal cells.

355
00:20:26.936 --> 00:20:28.076
A particular

356
00:20:29.836 --> 00:20:33.616
interest is that stromal immune cell types show

357
00:20:33.676 --> 00:20:34.496
quite a strong

358
00:20:35.376 --> 00:20:36.836
change, both in density

359
00:20:37.656 --> 00:20:38.876
and in their relationship

360
00:20:39.836 --> 00:20:43.116
to the epithelium. And because we also have

361
00:20:44.236 --> 00:20:46.936
had transcriptomics, we were able to look

362
00:20:47.276 --> 00:20:51.256
into which were the most prevalent cell

363
00:20:51.336 --> 00:20:53.036
functional state changes. And here,

364
00:20:53.856 --> 00:20:57.796
what's of interest is that fibroblasts and adipocytes showed

365
00:20:57.856 --> 00:21:01.456
by far the strongest transcriptional regulation as a function of age.

366
00:21:02.016 --> 00:21:05.676
In the case of fibroblasts, a fairly strong decrease

367
00:21:05.896 --> 00:21:06.116
in

368
00:21:07.156 --> 00:21:10.536
genes that are associated with ECM assembly and remodeling.

369
00:21:10.956 --> 00:21:12.676
They decrease as a function of age.

370
00:21:13.636 --> 00:21:17.336
The only transcript that sort of reached any level of significance, interestingly,

371
00:21:17.376 --> 00:21:20.866
was the leptin receptor. Leptin, as some of you will know, is

372
00:21:20.916 --> 00:21:24.756
involved in the hormonal signaling axis that has to do with lipid

373
00:21:24.776 --> 00:21:25.456
metabolism.

374
00:21:26.576 --> 00:21:30.236
And in contrast, adipocytes showed a very strong

375
00:21:30.316 --> 00:21:32.696
regulation. There were almost 90 genes that reached

376
00:21:33.576 --> 00:21:36.916
fairly large levels of significance, indicating that adipocytes

377
00:21:36.976 --> 00:21:40.056
were increasing in adipogenic factors and

378
00:21:40.136 --> 00:21:44.036
increasing lipid processing. Whereas among

379
00:21:44.136 --> 00:21:44.856
epithelium,

380
00:21:45.896 --> 00:21:49.696
the strongest influence was a gene that's probably involved in

381
00:21:49.776 --> 00:21:51.856
epithelial-mesenchymal communication.

382
00:21:52.536 --> 00:21:55.916
And so it communicates the idea that there seems to be a

383
00:21:55.936 --> 00:21:57.476
strong alteration,

384
00:21:58.356 --> 00:22:02.096
particularly in stroma, particularly in adipogenic stroma and

385
00:22:02.136 --> 00:22:05.956
fibroblasts, in conjunction with age-related declines

386
00:22:06.016 --> 00:22:06.176
in

387
00:22:07.576 --> 00:22:08.696
immune cell function.

388
00:22:09.816 --> 00:22:09.956
As

389
00:22:11.116 --> 00:22:14.696
you might expect, menopause, so when we stratified these

390
00:22:14.716 --> 00:22:16.476
patients as a function of age,

391
00:22:17.416 --> 00:22:20.736
the most variable features occur below the age of 50,

392
00:22:21.696 --> 00:22:25.576
and over the age of 50, the number of variable features

393
00:22:25.636 --> 00:22:28.976
is much diminished. So as has been well established,

394
00:22:29.756 --> 00:22:32.896
host endocrine signaling dominates many of these

395
00:22:33.176 --> 00:22:35.016
effects in the background.

396
00:22:36.056 --> 00:22:37.126
And so we arrive at

397
00:22:38.016 --> 00:22:41.966
the position where I think what we've seen in this preliminary study is

398
00:22:42.036 --> 00:22:45.836
that this is sort of the summary of what we saw, is that there's a total

399
00:22:45.876 --> 00:22:49.526
decrease in cellular elements, a decrease in some of the interactions

400
00:22:50.376 --> 00:22:51.556
which are comprised with

401
00:22:52.636 --> 00:22:56.416
decreases in cells that might be undertaking some

402
00:22:56.436 --> 00:22:59.176
level of immune surveillance as well as reaction, and

403
00:22:59.776 --> 00:23:03.586
alterations in inflammatory macrophages and adipocytes,

404
00:23:03.676 --> 00:23:07.176
which suggests that as the breast ages, there's

405
00:23:07.236 --> 00:23:09.716
increasing adipogenesis and inflammation.

406
00:23:10.396 --> 00:23:13.836
And I think it remains to be established how all this will

407
00:23:14.536 --> 00:23:18.476
feed into the surveillance of gene dosage mutations, but

408
00:23:18.976 --> 00:23:19.896
something for the future.

409
00:23:20.816 --> 00:23:24.616
So, I'd like to stop there, and I particularly want to

410
00:23:24.676 --> 00:23:28.516
thank Vinci Au and Eric Li, who led within my lab

411
00:23:28.556 --> 00:23:30.126
many of these studies, and acknowledge

412
00:23:31.316 --> 00:23:34.456
my collaborators in Cambridge, Raza Ali and Pulkit Gupta,

413
00:23:34.556 --> 00:23:37.626
who worked on the IMC study, and Joan Gray,

414
00:23:38.676 --> 00:23:42.636
and a long-standing collaboration with Sarab, which we worked with on the

415
00:23:42.696 --> 00:23:46.156
lineage epithelium, as well as our funders, the Gray Foundation,

416
00:23:46.256 --> 00:23:49.836
BCRF, and BC Cancer. I'll stop there.

417
00:23:49.876 --> 00:23:51.236
Thanks.

418
00:23:57.256 --> 00:23:59.376
Thank you. Questions. If you have questions, please use the mic.

419
00:24:02.096 --> 00:24:02.676
I see Nick.

420
00:24:03.056 --> 00:24:04.496
Oh, okay. All right. I'll start.

421
00:24:05.396 --> 00:24:09.226
Yeah, wonderful talk, Sam. I was wondering, in our normal

422
00:24:09.316 --> 00:24:13.256
breast atlas as well, when we try to compare metadata for aging and menopause, it

423
00:24:13.276 --> 00:24:15.636
was pretty hard to distinguish between the two of those.

424
00:24:15.676 --> 00:24:16.305
I was wondering

425
00:24:17.236 --> 00:24:20.976
if you could attribute some of these changes directly to

426
00:24:21.016 --> 00:24:24.276
menopause versus... kind of aging-related differences.

427
00:24:24.626 --> 00:24:27.466
And I guess you can look at the period before and after menopause maybe to get a

428
00:24:27.486 --> 00:24:28.046
better idea.

429
00:24:28.806 --> 00:24:30.966
Yeah. That's a great question.

430
00:24:32.326 --> 00:24:34.726
I think there's two elements to this.

431
00:24:34.866 --> 00:24:38.766
One is that menopause is actually a very difficult

432
00:24:38.866 --> 00:24:42.286
state to define precisely, because it's a

433
00:24:42.326 --> 00:24:46.196
physiological shift in host endocrine signaling that takes place over a number of

434
00:24:46.286 --> 00:24:46.616
years.

435
00:24:47.526 --> 00:24:51.486
And the clinical way that it's often done is people

436
00:24:51.506 --> 00:24:55.445
do a questionnaire and they say yes or no, but that doesn't actually represent

437
00:24:55.486 --> 00:24:57.886
the biological state. So typically,

438
00:24:59.326 --> 00:25:03.286
sort of clinician-determined menopause is not such a great way of

439
00:25:03.326 --> 00:25:06.466
doing. But here we do have age-continuous measurements,

440
00:25:06.546 --> 00:25:10.496
and in some earlier work, we had shown that

441
00:25:10.786 --> 00:25:14.766
there's a very strong age-correlated change in

442
00:25:14.846 --> 00:25:16.886
transcription and gene expression for

443
00:25:17.906 --> 00:25:20.866
some epigenetic drivers as well as ER drivers.

444
00:25:20.946 --> 00:25:23.116
So if you look at ER signaling,

445
00:25:24.046 --> 00:25:27.436
proteins like GATA3 related proteins and

446
00:25:27.506 --> 00:25:31.326
FOXA1 and so on, you can see that they are sort of colinearly

447
00:25:31.346 --> 00:25:35.336
correlated with age, which implies, I think, that those transcripts could

448
00:25:35.446 --> 00:25:39.226
be hormonally responsive. And I think there's now data that

449
00:25:39.266 --> 00:25:43.026
shows that EZH2 and its trimethyl mark, which we

450
00:25:43.066 --> 00:25:46.886
earlier had showed has a very strong age correlation, are in fact ER

451
00:25:46.896 --> 00:25:50.806
responsive genes. So I think you can tie some of these things to endocrine

452
00:25:50.886 --> 00:25:54.566
signaling. But I completely take your point that quite

453
00:25:54.606 --> 00:25:58.506
aside from that, one would like to sort of subtract that signal out

454
00:25:59.186 --> 00:26:00.326
and look at the

455
00:26:01.226 --> 00:26:05.126
remainder. And it's quite hard because the endocrine signal is

456
00:26:05.186 --> 00:26:08.866
so strong in the background that I think it's tricky,

457
00:26:08.966 --> 00:26:10.726
but I'm sure both contribute.

458
00:26:11.786 --> 00:26:12.666
Thanks. Beautiful work.

459
00:26:13.286 --> 00:26:14.266
More questions?

460
00:26:14.446 --> 00:26:18.366
Yes, thanks. Wonderful talk. So I have, I think, more of a broad

461
00:26:18.686 --> 00:26:22.006
question. Well, I think it will feed into a broad question is, what's your sense of

462
00:26:22.066 --> 00:26:25.986
BRCA1 and BRCA2 in terms of their actual role with

463
00:26:26.006 --> 00:26:28.886
the normal tissues in terms of heterozygotes and mutations?

464
00:26:29.006 --> 00:26:32.906
I know you showed a slightly increased rate of copy number alterations or

465
00:26:33.165 --> 00:26:36.326
these aneuploidies within the heterozygote carriers.

466
00:26:36.766 --> 00:26:37.886
Is there any evidence that

467
00:26:38.766 --> 00:26:41.686
in those heterozygotes that HR might be somehow involved?

468
00:26:41.735 --> 00:26:45.346
Any evidence of seeing, if you look at the individual reads, evidence of

469
00:26:45.386 --> 00:26:47.466
micromol immediate deletions, et cetera?

470
00:26:47.546 --> 00:26:50.446
Or, I guess, what are your general thoughts on those processes?

471
00:26:50.486 --> 00:26:54.346
Or is it maybe a more permissive environment when you have those heterozygotes, so

472
00:26:54.426 --> 00:26:57.786
they facilitate these changes, but they're not mechanistically linked

473
00:26:57.826 --> 00:26:59.705
to BRCA1, BRCA2?

474
00:27:00.826 --> 00:27:03.586
Yeah. It's a great question, and I would say,

475
00:27:04.866 --> 00:27:07.306
an unresolved one is the question of, is there

476
00:27:08.786 --> 00:27:12.346
a BRCA heterozygous intermediate

477
00:27:12.366 --> 00:27:16.126
phenotype, or is it more that by losing one allele, you're

478
00:27:16.186 --> 00:27:16.735
creating

479
00:27:17.566 --> 00:27:21.326
the sort of chances of losing two alleles is now greater, and it's really just that

480
00:27:21.366 --> 00:27:25.206
you're biasing the forward chances that a cell gets a second hit?

481
00:27:26.946 --> 00:27:30.626
We didn't see sort of read-based

482
00:27:31.486 --> 00:27:34.866
HRD-like signatures as far as we could see.

483
00:27:35.106 --> 00:27:39.066
The sequencing is quite shallow, so it also would be hard to resolve.

484
00:27:39.936 --> 00:27:43.526
There probably are intermediate phenotypes that you can see because

485
00:27:44.606 --> 00:27:44.846
in

486
00:27:45.826 --> 00:27:49.586
methylation patterns, we think there's probably an intermediate methylation

487
00:27:49.646 --> 00:27:50.526
state pattern, which

488
00:27:51.486 --> 00:27:54.186
is yet to be really sort of fully pinned down.

489
00:27:54.746 --> 00:27:58.326
And the other intermediate phenotype that has been described, but I don't think we

490
00:27:58.386 --> 00:28:02.286
really saw it here, was in telomere erosion, because

491
00:28:02.546 --> 00:28:05.426
telomere length is partly

492
00:28:05.786 --> 00:28:08.706
dependent on homology directed repair.

493
00:28:09.506 --> 00:28:13.006
And it seems like there might be an intermediate state there, where if you only

494
00:28:13.066 --> 00:28:14.106
have half of the

495
00:28:15.126 --> 00:28:19.066
key protein, that it will affect the rate at which

496
00:28:19.126 --> 00:28:23.006
telomere repair can happen. We didn't see it in this study, but I think

497
00:28:23.066 --> 00:28:25.526
it's quite possibly there.

498
00:28:26.006 --> 00:28:28.006
Yeah. Sorry. Very quick because I'm very curious.

499
00:28:28.026 --> 00:28:31.056
So that methylation phenotype, is that specifically at the BRCA1 promoter, or is

500
00:28:31.086 --> 00:28:32.096
that a global phenotype?

501
00:28:32.166 --> 00:28:34.706
No, I'm talking about global genome-wide methylation.

502
00:28:34.806 --> 00:28:36.346
It seems to be a little different.

503
00:28:37.786 --> 00:28:39.946
Don't know what the basis of that is. Yeah.

504
00:28:40.006 --> 00:28:42.506
Great talk. I was wondering whether you have used the

505
00:28:43.026 --> 00:28:46.706
spatial transcriptome to infer the aneuploidy as we

506
00:28:46.786 --> 00:28:48.646
age as well, or-

507
00:28:49.266 --> 00:28:49.616
The... Is the que-

508
00:28:49.616 --> 00:28:52.606
... use things like InferCNV or similar-

509
00:28:53.166 --> 00:28:53.426
Oh

510
00:28:53.486 --> 00:28:56.786
... to try to infer to the aneuploidy as

511
00:28:57.106 --> 00:28:58.206
aging progresses?

512
00:28:59.146 --> 00:29:03.086
Yeah. That's a great question. We're trying to look at that.

513
00:29:03.166 --> 00:29:06.806
It's quite hard. I think, inferring in

514
